Although git supports symlinks, these are platform-dependant in terms of:
    - Operating system
        - User permissions (Windows)
    - File system

Initial set up must be performed with the correct script as follows:

#==========#===================================================================#
|          |                          Operating System                         |
| Symlinks +---------------------------+--------------+------------------------+
|          | Linux                     | Windows <10  | Windows 10+ [1]        |
#==========#===========================#==============#========================#
| Yes      | setup_linux_symlink.bash  |    (N/A)     | setup_Win10_mklink.bat |
#----------+---------------------------+--------------+------------------------#
| No       | setup_linux.bash          |            setup_Win10.bat            |
#==========#===========================#==============#========================#

Note also that non-symlink modes of operation require re-running these scripts
for updates in www to be propaged to the project.

[1] By default, symlinks are not enabled and require "developer mode" to be
enabled - this does not remove file system restrictions
